‘It’s all been done,’ goes the defeatist mantra. Deep observation of one's creative universe will change it and the observer and reveal its endless nature.

This famous photography spot at the Griffith Observatory in Los Angeles begged for fresh interpretation. I programmed my motion-control robots on-site and barely got a time-lapse shot off before security kicked us out for the night. The sound was created with my friend James and his wall of modular synthesizers.

My first mint of 2023. Btw, last year I made my living exclusively through art. No commercial projects. That's a first for me. Huge thank you to my collectors, the curators who put me in gallery and museum shows (both real and virtual), and you. ❤️

In 2013, I turned the world upside down with my agnostic ritual, Circle of Abstract Ritual.

I plunged into the void with open eyes. I captured 300,000 photos of wildfires, riots, & paintings in abandoned houses. I asked if creation & destruction are the same.

COAR is more than art, it’s an attempt to peer into the religion-sized hole in culture & myself. I asked, Can I activate the 'mechanics of ritual' without belief, dogma, or even intention through a creative act? It is radical inclusivity. Anyone can take part. No gatekeepers needed.

@reuben was kind enough to send me a few words on how it shaped his own art:

“I first encountered Circle of Abstract Ritual in 2014 at a time when I was struggling to figure out what my path would be; there was very little that inspired me. Seeing COAR changed this. It energized me and made me believe in the power of photography, video, and music as a unified force. COAR inspired me and so many others.”

Every volunteer who stepped into the circle of upside-down Joshua Trees -destroyed in wildfires and salvaged as sculptures by my late friend, Shig- had their own inexplicable experiences. It became an intersection of art, community, & the unexplainable.

Nearly 1M views & a decade later, COAR is as relevant as ever. This timeless dialogue between experiment, reality, and art empowers our understanding of community through the reinvention of ritual. 

This is the first of many artworks expanding and revisiting, COAR. It is derrived from Circle of Abstract Ritual, expanded, remastered, and recolored from the original footage in 4K.

A giant sequoia caught an ember in its upper branches during the Windy Fire in 2021.

Branches as big as trees were falling to the ground (slide 3) & firefighters told @stuartpalley & I this tree would die a slow death.

We chainsawed our way thru 50 downed trees & moved a dozen boulders getting in.

Getting back out late at night before something fell on us was harrowing (slide 2). 

@goodmorningamerica saw my photo in NatGeo & climbed the tree for a story. To everyone's surprise, it survived!

We've lost 20% of the entire population of giant sequoias in the last 2 yrs due to wildfires.

Pls donate to @sequoiaparksconservancy 💚🙏

A piece that had a huge impact on my internal and external world. Challenging in every way, and a break through on multiple levels as well. RIP my friends.

Optical illusion paintings are not really about the illusion. They're portals in spacetime. They're portals in minds. 

I can't make an illusion without also breaking it because they're just as compelling out of perspective as in. 

They're a long journey in one step. They're shapeshifters, transmuters, and plot devices. 

Go in one and come out different.

Illusion paintings *out* of perspective. 

Left out the in perspective compositions bc I like the idea of seeing these as their own “analog generative” abstractions and not dependant on the illusion.

I repainted these burned out cars for 18 months over and over. I started off intentionally minimal with white, like a blank canvas. Then I painted a “wave coming into shore from above” as an optical illusion that dipped below the horizon. 

Then, I went back over and over to record the accumulating graffiti.

I brought artist friends* once, and finally, I repainted the whole thing in a rainbow gradient. 

It's called Ghosts of the Future. It's the centerpiece of a new film of the same name.

Thinking of art lately as a form of kintsugi. Art is the gold between the cracks refusing the shattered pieces of nature and humans back together in beautifully scarred harmony. Lessons etched in idiosyncratic lines across natural history. 

Spending months in the trees this year has been incredibly healing and clarifying in countless ways. I learned true self love hanging out with pine trees in Big Bear.

Instead of extracting something from nature, sometimes even a pretty picture, try simply being in it. Breathing. Wandering without agenda. Smile. Laugh. It will wind up being the most productive use of your time in ages.

Up until three years ago, I simply wasn't focused on public-facing events or exhibitions. Since then, I've been in 30-40 museums, plenty of exhibitions, film festivals, art fairs, and even performed a soundart set at @desertdaze_official (!!!) (courtesy of @cristophercichocki)

I appreciate the many curators, fellow artists, museums, galleries, and event staff who put me into shows and put on shows. ♥️

There's an obnoxiously long highlight in my bio if you want to see more titled “SHOWS.”

It helps to look at all this craziness now and again to remember what I managed to pull off during three of the most difficult years of my life. I'm proud of myself for making it through all this and lucky to have such great friends and supporters. 🙏

The most heartbreaking thing I ever shot was giant sequoias burning. 

Trees are our grandfathers and keepers of wisdom. It is impossible not to feel a sense of something greater than ourselves in their presence. 💚🌲

The @sequoiaparksconservancy featured one of my photos on the cover of this report. It’s not a big fancy publication, but they’re the group working to conserve the giant sequoias and for that reason it’s far more meaningful to me. 

Shot on assign for @natgeo with @stuartpalley 

I urge you to donate to this organization and support all efforts to stop the destruction of ancient forests.
